<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>AFS0061</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0061</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> COMPASS-Suffolk </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 16pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPASS was a parent-led campaign group local to the Great Cornard Upper School</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> (GCUS) pyramid in South Suffolk. The group formed in the autumn of 2010 to ensure that there was open debate on a proposed Free School in Stoke by Nayland (a village in the catchment area for GCUS) and to inform local parents and community members about t</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">he implications of a new Free School in the area. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">This submission sets out in brief our experience as a parent-led group in Suffolk in regard to proposed Free Schools. It provides evidence for point 1 of the Committee</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">s enquiry: </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The process for approving</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:20pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">SUMMARY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">In 2011 the Stoke by Nayland Academy Trust (SbNAT) applied to the DfE to open an 11-16 school in Stoke by Nayland (a village in South Suffolk). This bid was</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> unsuccessful. The Seckford Foundation then applied to the DfE in 2012 to open an 11-16 school on the same site. This bid was also unsuccessful.</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Stoke by Nayland is in a part of Suffolk with a significant surplus of secondary-school places. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPASS formed</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> in response to a free school proposal in Stoke by Nayland, in order to promote open debate about the issues that would arise should the free school bid be successful. Both SbNAT and the Seckford Foundation refused to engage in public debate with us.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPA</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">SS submitted a thorough explanation of our grounds for opposing the school to the DfE in both 2011 and 2012, and requested a meeting to discuss these further. On both occasions we were advised that there was no opportunity to raise our concerns with the Df</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">E until or unless the bids reached the </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">pre-opening</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">stage. We considered this a weakness in the free schools application process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPASS</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">s view was (and remains) that it is not possible to establish a new school in an area with a large surplus of school </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">places without it having a negative impact on existing provision and the wider community. Therefore the application process should include, at an early stage, the promotion of open public debate and an opportunity for those opposing the proposal to be hear</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">d. Instead, there was a culture of secrecy about both the free school proposals and the application process. This was perpetuated by the DfE</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">s refusal to meet with us and hear our concerns. </span></p><p style="margin:20pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">BACKGROUND AND HISTORY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Context and Stoke by Nayland Academy</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Trust</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The proposed closure of middle schools in Suffolk (a process known locally as the Schools Organisation Review or SOR) coincided from 2010 with the opportunity for parent-led groups to apply to the DfE to open a Free School. This led to a number of f</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">ree school applications in the county for 11-16 schools, all in small towns where there was some parental opposition to the closure of the middle schools. In 2011 a parent-led group, the Stoke by Nayland Academy Trust (SbNAT), applied to open an 11-16 scho</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">ol in Stoke by Nayland from September 2013, intending to use the site of the middle school in that village which was set to close in July 2013.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Establishment and make-up of COMPASS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPASS was formed in response to that application. We were concerned abo</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">ut the absence of informed debate about the benefits and potential risks of a new 11-16 free school in Stoke by Nayland, and formed COMPASS as a campaign group in order to promote open debate on the issue.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPASS was a single-issue community campaign group with no political affiliation </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">though some individual members and supporters do hold a range of strong political views. It had a core organising group of eight: six parents with children at GCUS and loca</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">l primary schools, one of whom was also a governor at GCUS and another of whom was on the equivalent of the PTA. Two further members were teachers at GCUS, one of whom is also a Liberal Democrat councillor.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Campaign</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPASS held a number of public events a</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">t local schools </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">both formal meetings and informal drop-in sessions, and provided information which was publicised on our website and via social media, and circulated to parents by the schools in the GCUS pyramid (with permission from the headteachers inv</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">olved). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Having gained local support from parents and community-members in the area that would have been affected by the opening of a new school, COMPASS organised a petition opposing the free school. This was submitted to the DfE, alongside a document out</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">lining the reasons for our opposition to the proposed free school, to coincide with the deadline for Free School applications. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The proposal by SbNAT was rejected by the DfE.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Seckford Foundation Proposal</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">In 2012 SbNAT ceded control of the bid for an 11-16 </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">school in Stoke by Nayland to the Seckford Foundation (who had also bid to open two more free schools in Suffolk </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Beccles and Saxmundham). COMPASS continued to provide opportunities for local debate on the proposed free school. We again submitted a compre</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">hensive document to the DfE outlining our opposition to the proposed school, with a request to meet the DfE and discuss our concerns in greater depth. The proposal by the Seckford Foundation in 2012 was also rejected by the DfE.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Outcome</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The two application</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">s to run an 11-16 Free School in Stoke by Nayland were both rejected. COMPASS as a campaign group is therefore no longer active, although members of the group continue to be actively involved in schools in the area.</span></p><p style="margin:20pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">COMPASS</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">S POSITION</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Our concerns fell int</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">o three categories:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.15pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The actual school offer from the proposing groups (paragraphs 16-17);</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.15pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The lack of transparency or opportunity for open public debate in the free school application process at conceptual and application stages (paragraphs 18-24);</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.15pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">impact that opening a new 11-16 school in our area would have on existing schools and the Schools Reorganisation already underway in Suffolk (paragraphs 25-30).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Educational Offer</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Both proposers sought to provide a small secondary school and, in their focus</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> on academic subjects, struggled to avoid the association that their school would be selective. As such their proposals were divisive. The proposals were carefully marketed and drew heavily on anger amongst some parents about the proposed closure of the mi</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">ddle school, and claims that could not be substantiated (such as the value of small schools). Because of the lack of public debate, it was not possible to test out these assumptions in a calm and measured way to enable parents to make a fully informed choi</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">ce about what was on offer.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">There were a number of other concerns about the actual school offer in both years, but these are not explored in this document as the proposals were unsuccessful.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of Transparency</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Neither SbNAT nor the Seckford Foundation </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">made their business cases for the proposed school available to the public. Neither organisation provided information about the numbers registering for the proposed schools, despite requests to do so. It was therefore impossible for the bidders to respond a</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">dequately to the concerns of local parents about the educational offer they would be in a position to make should their application have been successful, or about the impact that the proposed school would have had on existing schools.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of clarity</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">From </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">the outset in 2010 it was also difficult to discern the difference between local anger at the closure of middle schools and local support for the proposed free schools. Free schools were publicised as extending choice following the closure of middle school</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">s, even though the closure of middle schools did not reduce choice of school, simply the year groups at which pupils change schools. It is therefore possible that proposers and DfE may have colluded in allowing those opposing closure of the middle schools </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">to feel </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">mistakenly </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">that their voice had been heard.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of accountability of the proposers to the local community</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">SbNAT refused to enter into public debate with COMPASS, and instead sought to denigrate our campaign. The Seckford Foundation did provide</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> communications events for parents to find out about the proposed school and to invite registrations, but refused to acknowledge the existence of local opposition or to enter into open dialogue about the proposed free school. Both argued </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">and the free sch</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">ool application process supported this position </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">that the free school proposals could be considered in isolation from the impact they may have on existing provision and that there was no need for discussion with the wider community at that stage of the pr</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">oceedings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Freedom of Information Requests (FoI)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Given the paucity of information available about the decision-making process for approving a free school and the actual bids submitted by SbNAT and the Seckford Foundation, COMPASS sought to use Freedom of Information requests to elicit more detailed infor</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">mation about the applications and approval process. However on a number of occasions, information requested via FoI was turned down on the grounds that it was not in the public interest, and still refused following further challenge. Unsuccessful FoIs incl</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">uded: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.35pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">a request in July 2011 to establish the evidence of demand contained in the SbNAT free school application;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.35pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">a request in October 2011 enquiring about the reasons the SbNAT bid was rejected;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 46.35pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">a request in April 2012 for the release of minutes, notes or</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> action points from a meeting held in November 2011 to discuss free schools in Suffolk between DfE and Suffolk County Council (SCC) officials.  FoI was served to both DfE and SCC in this case; following appeal to both organisations the final response was t</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">hat no notes or action points were recorded.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Responses received from the DfE to our FoI requests served only to heighten our concerns about the lack of transparency in the free school application process, and raised further questions about the robustness o</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">f the process.  The following extract is an example.  It is taken from the DfE response to an appeal about the refusal to release information about the reasons the SbNAT bid was rejected:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The panel also discussed the points raised in your email of 1 Janua</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ry 2012.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 48pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">It is in the public interest to understand why a free school application has failed, because public money has been spent in the course of the process, and there is a general presumption that government should be open and transparent.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 48pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">It is in the</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> public interest to know the general reasons why free school applications have failed, as this is likely to be of use to other Free School applicants who can then adapt applications accordingly.</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">We do not publish the reasons for failure of individual proj</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ects because the process is competitive, where applications are compared against each other and a range of contextual information is taken account. This means that there is no minimum benchmark for an application to be successful because it is dependent on</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> the number and quality of applications received within the round. This could potentially vary significantly from one round to the next. Therefore, releasing information about individual unsuccessful projects may be unhelpful to future applicants and could</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> stifle innovative solutions.</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">No democratic process</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPASS sought unsuccessfully to discuss our concerns with the DfE in 2011 and 2012. The DfE</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">s position was that wider discussion about a free school would only be held if the application were through to the pre-opening stage. Given that pre-opening de facto implies that a school will open, this effectively renders invalid any local opposition to </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">the proposal and severely limits any potential for democratic process. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on Existing Schools</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Suffolk is a relatively small LEA but has a significant surplus of secondary school places </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">particularly in the areas in which free schools were proposed (o</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">r have since opened).  This point was put to the DfE by the Local Authority. By 2016, given the existing level of surplus plus the provision of additional 11-16 free schools, nearly one third of the secondary school places planned for Suffolk will not be u</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">sed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">This is important because carrying a significant surplus of places leads to consequent burdens in cost, and reduces the cost-effectiveness of education spending in the authority overall. It should be noted that in Suffolk, per-capita funding at key s</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">tage 4 is already lower than in other LEAs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Local Authority data made it clear that an additional free school in Stoke by Nayland would add more surplus places, and place significant financial strain on existing schools, including GCUS, should pupils who </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">were expected to attend existing schools instead go to the new free school. Through a consequent reduction in budget, this in turn would reduce the educational offer existing schools could make to their remaining pupils. Thus the opening of a free school i</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">n a locality with surplus places could lead to a reduction in educational offer for all local pupils </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">as clearly acknowledged in the DfE</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">s own impact assessment for Saxmundham Free School which was only recently made public.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on SOR </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 39.25pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt">(N.B. Paragraph</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt">s 24-26 concern the context in Suffolk, rather than the case of Stoke by Nayland </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">per se</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:11pt">.)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The DfE inviting (and in some cases approving) applications for free schools in Suffolk at the same time the Local Authority was already undertaking a major reorganis</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">ation of schools in the county has complicated planning for the Authority, for schools and for local parents. It will also make it impossible to ascertain whether any future successes or failures are due to the advent of the free schools or the closure of </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">the middle schools. This is because it has resulted in a piecemeal approach to raising standards in the county rather than a strategic response. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">The free schools that have been opened in Suffolk (and the proposed one in Stoke by Nayland) are all small secondary schools. The DfE and Local Authority appear to hold contradictory views about the size of secondary schools: the Authority proposed 1200 pu</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">pils as the optimum number for a school to be financially viable and offer a broad and balanced curriculum, yet the free school proposals have all been for schools of 540 pupils maximum.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Suffolk is a rural county. Schools therefore rely on school transpo</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">rt arrangements, responsibility for which remains with the Local Authority. The DfE required Local Authorities to provide transport to free schools, yet the process of approving free schools in Suffolk occurred without reference to the need for school plac</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">es. This raises the very real possibility that the introduction of free schools in an area may reduce parental choice, not expand it, because parents in a rural area may need to make choice based on how their children will get to school.</span></p><p style="margin:20pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">CONCLUSIONS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">COMPAS</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">S was formed to promote public debate about a proposed free school and facilitate expression of local opposition to that proposal. It was formed because the Free School application process as it stands at present does not facilitate open dialogue with the </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">community or proper public testing of proposals and the assumptions within them at an early enough stage. This includes, crucially, no open acknowledgement of the impact a new free school in a locality with surplus places could have on existing provision. </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">Thus what could be an exercise in bringing together community stakeholders to support local schools instead becomes divisive and wasteful of resources.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 19.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">In submitting this evidence to the Select Committee, COMPASS are hopeful that the Committee will cons</span><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">ider the need for more transparency and open debate as part of the Free Schools application process going forward. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Optima; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:10pt">Great Cornard Upper School changed its name in September 2013 to Thomas Gainsborough School</span></p></body></html>